). \nThere are other pieces of information that seem to confirm that this a public university: \nArticle 34 makes reference to the budget. A portion comes from the State: The University\'s budget revenues shall consist of: a) The annual amounts allotted for the University in the State Budget. b) Return of its fixed and movable revenues. c) Donations, gifts, grants, bequests and endowment that the Board of Trustees approves. d) University fees and educational services and research fees. e) Any other revenues stated in the laws and bylaws. \nThe website makes reference to the a meeting of the Board of Trustees held in 2017. The chairmanship of the Board is under the Minister of Education (http://www.uob.edu.bh/en/index.php/15-slider/1627-board-of-trustees-uob-to-develop-graduate-programs-and-establish-new-disciplines). \nThe university has 26,000 students. Normally, private university except perhaps in large countries do not have such large enrollement. \nThe meeting of the board makes reference to the “annual report to assess the academic, administrative and financial aspects of the University and its strategic plan” and to the report of the Audit and Finance Committee and its recommendations”. Those documents might also confirm the public status of the university. I could not find them in the website. \nThe following top universities website also features the University of Bahrain as a public university (https://www.topuniversities.com/universities/university-bahrain/undergrad).\nEventually, you might also with to check the GUPES (Global University Partnership on Environment and Sustainability) colleagues at the Ecosystems Division.\nBest regards.\nIsabel',17,'2018-07-02 04:41:30',NULL,NULL,0),(113,496,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,'AssesmentQuestions','partners','OK. I recommend this partnership',226,'2018-07-03 11:21:29',NULL,NULL,0),(114,496,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,'AssesmentQuestions','partners','OK. I recommend this partnership',226,'2018-07-03 11:22:10',NULL,NULL,0),(115,496,NULL