ed Huawei and Hikvision for complicity in China\'s increasing repression and forced assimilation of the Uyghur people, for continuing to supply the police state with equipment. https://bit.ly/2PTqbI3 \n\n•	Huawei was criticized for misleading consumers by promoting digital camera-captured images as smartphone shots. https://bit.ly/2M3cAw8 \n\n•	Several companies, including Huawei were criticized for failing to address cobalt supply chain issues in the Democratic Republic of Congo. In an Amnesty International report titled “Time to Recharge”. Amnesty International has also found that Huawei, and other companies cited in its 2016 report, “This is What We Die For”, have failed to address several supply chain issues, including child labour and occupational safety, associated with cobalt sourced from a primary supplier of cobalt referred to as Zhejiang Huayou. (Translated from Arabic) https://translate.google.com/translate?sl=auto&tl=en&u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.ida2at.com%2Fchild-labor-in-cobalt-mining-for-batteries%2F \n\n•	Samsung Electronics, SK Hynix, and Micron Technology are being investigated for alleged price fixing in China. According to a Financial Times article published on November 19, 2018 China\'s Anti-Monopoly Bureau has evidence of large-scale violations of the country\'s antitrust laws allegedly committed by Samsung Electronics, SK Hynix, and Micron Technology. Authorities had launched investigations in late May 2018 on suspicions that the companies fixed prices of Dynamic Random-Access Memory chips (DRAM chips) following a reported 47 percent price hike for these products in 2017. The companies, whose offices were reportedly raided, could face fines of up to $2.5 billion each. DRAM chips are reportedly used in Apple\'s and Huawei\'s smart phones and in computers produced by Samsung. Separately, in early November 2018, the US administration launched criminal proceedings against Fujian Jinhua for alleged theft of trade secrets. (Translated from French) https://bit.ly/2Fmkct9 \n\nLegal cases involving Huawei Technologies Co., Ltd.:\nDisclaimer: the legal cases mentioned within this news report are not exhaustive.\n1)	United States authorities have accused the Chief Finance Officer (CFO) Meng Wanzhou of Huawei Technologies in giving misleading statements to banks about its relationship with Skycom Tech, which operated in Iran, causing the banks to process hundreds of millions of dollars in transactions that may have violated US sanctions against Iran. Huawei in fact operated Skycom as an unofficial subsidiary (Skycom was reportedly dissolved in 2017). During one presentation in 2013 to an international bank, the CFO supposedly stated that Huawei and Skycom were unrelated, leading banks to clear its transactions. https://cnb.cx/2FhKE72 \n\nThe US Department of Justice had initiated a criminal probe into the said matter after subpoenas had been issued from the Department of Commerce and the Office of Foreign Assets Control. A Vancouver court granted the CFO, a CAD 10 million ($7.5 million) bail after she was arrested by local authorities at the request of the US government. Under the conditions of the bail, Meng must wear an ankle monitor and stay at her Canadian domicile between certain hours. Furthermore, five of Meng’s friends pledged equity in their homes and funds as a guarantee that the CFO will not leave the country. https://on.wsj.com/2QA0tLB\n\n2)	Singapore’s High Court ordered Huawei to pay $36 million in damages to Creative Technologies (CT) for breaching a contract related to a wireless network project. In 2010, CT contracted Huawei to design, build and operate wireless network in Singapore called WiMax. Under the terms of the agreement, Huawei was required to provide nationwide wireless coverage with 225 base stations. In 2012, CT filed a lawsuit against Huawei and claimed that the company miscalculated and misrepresented the cost of the network. https://bit.ly/2D3FjxU \n\n3)	Ukraine-based subsidiaries of multinational companies including Huawei Ukraine, and others have been accused of evading a total of UAH 1.5 billion in taxes using a scheme to pay the out-staffing companies Promotion Outsourcing and Promotion Staff for fictitious services for five years. Meanwhile, the defence of the accused companies has alleged that the expert\'s report provided by the Research Information and Consultation Center, which found that state coffers received over UAH 955 million ($33 million) less tax revenues, and was conducted with severe violations of Ukrainian legislation. https://bit.ly/2SOPDzc\n\n4)	Poland has arrested a Chinese employee of Huawei and a Polish national involved in cyber-business on allegations of spying, Polish state media has reported, deepening the controversy over western criticism of the Chinese telecoms company. However, a spokesman for the Polish security services told Reuters the allegations are related to individual actions, and were not linked directly to Huawei. US intelligence agencies claim Huawei Technologies Co Ltd is linked to China’s government and its equipment could contain “backdoors” for use by government spies. No evidence has been produced publicly and the company has repeatedly denied the allegations. But the criticism has led several western countries and businesses to consider whether they should allow Huawei’s equipment to be used in their telecoms networks. https://bit.ly/2TLU4ek \n\n',2190,'2019-01-14 13:47:14',NULL,NULL,0),(721,479,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,'Comments','partners','Dear Mohammed, I have included the comments to your questions, but I am not sure you received the tag for it. Kindly review my comments above. ',1451,'2019-01-14 15:45:52',NULL,NULL,0),(722,479,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,'Comments','partners',' Dear Mohammed, I have included the comments to your questions, but I am not sure you received the tag for it. Kindly review my comments above.',1451,'2019-01-14 15:46:45',NULL,NULL,0),(723,1268,1014,NULL,NULL,2,'AgreementSummary','agreements