obtained from the organization’s most recent annual reports and website. However, in the case of the current partner, while the legal status has been confirmed, there is no company website to obtain further information regarding the partner. The partner’s financial capacity cannot be evaluated since the partner has no financial statements as the entity was established in April 2018.  \n\nAs to the technical capacity of the partner the only information available is that found in the due diligence which indicates that the partner has worked with other UN Environment offices and the CBD Secretariat. In particular, the due diligence indicates that ESSA Synergy has been involved in the development of the previous fifth national CBD report and has been selected by the Macedonia Ministry of Environment and Physical Planning and Project Steering Committee to implement the project assignment.  \n\nIt is important to note that UN Environment partners are subject to an internal review and due diligence process which should allow UN Environment to individually engage such partners to minimize such risks associated with the engagement of such partners.  \n\n Given the status of the partner, I would recommend a more thorough review of the partnership. My suggestions are as follows: \n\na)	Could the submitting office clarify the legal basis for the relationship on which the partner could implement such previous activities;\nb)	The submitting office should attach any document signed with UN Environment- legal instruments or otherwise to indicate that the partner is engaged with UN Environment and what these deliverables are;\nc)	Submitting office should provide reports from the partner and confirmation from the other UN Environment offices that the deliverables for previous activities implemented by the partner have been accomplished as required within UN Environment standards of evaluation. I understand that if such activities exist, these are ongoing tasks and therefore it is sti