 previous fifth national CBD report and has been selected by the Macedonia Ministry of Environment and Physical Planning and Project Steering Committee to implement the project assignment. It is important to note that UN Environment partners are subject to an internal review and due diligence process which should allow UN Environment to individually engage such partners to minimize such risks associated with the engagement of such partners. Given the status of the partner, I would recommend a more thorough review of the partnership. My suggestions are as follows: a) Could the submitting office clarify the legal basis for the relationship on which the partner could implement such previous activities; b) The submitting office should attach any document signed with UN Environment- legal instruments or otherwise to indicate that the partner is engaged with UN Environment and what these deliverables are; c) Submitting office should provide reports from the partner and confirmation from the other UN Environment offices that the deliverables for previous activities implemented by the partner have been accomplished as required within UN Environment standards of evaluation. I understand that if such activities exist, these are ongoing tasks and therefore it is still difficult to evaluate the technical capacity of the partner. Until such activities are finalized and it is determined that the deliverables have been accomplished based on such reports. For record purposes, the portal should contain such information for audit purposes so that it is specifically clear why the partner is being approved. ',28,'2019-02-26 11:53:30',NULL,NULL,0),(841,1375,1161,NULL,NULL,2,'AgreementSummary','agreements','Changes as discussed',2333,'2019-02-26 12:41:14',NULL,NULL,0),(842,469,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,'AssesmentQuestions','partners','Lorna - if this is your \"first private sector partner\", why is the assessment being done as a non-profit partner, and the answer to question 4 \"No\"? Please clar