                                      \n Does GPIC have a copy of their Certificate of incorporate and Articles of Association in the English language? \n\nI have also reviewed the risk assessment which does not provide very concrete steps to be taken to ensure this company complies with certain environmental standards. It simply states as follows: \"The UN Environment Regional Office West Asia will continuously monitor the partnership and the activities of GPIC and respond to risks that may arise accordingly.\" It is important that the West Asia Office identifies,  concrete steps that will be taken to respond to such risks which may arise. \n\n\nThat being said, I understand that GPIC has taken some steps to manage greenhouse gas emissions. They have done this by commissioning the Middle East’s first carbon dioxide recovery plant at GPIC in 2010. the plant has the capacity to capture 450 metric tons of carbon dioxide per day from the reformer flue gases to improve its carbon footprint. \n\nAnother way to ensure oversight and to ensure a reduction in risks is for the GPIC to consider being a partner in the Climate and Clean Air Coalition as a non-state partner. The Climate and Clean Air Coalition is a voluntary partnership of governments, intergovernmental organizations, businesses, scientific institutions and civil society organizations committed to improving air quality and protecting the climate through actions to reduce short-lived climate pollutants.\n\nCCAC was formed by the governments of Bangladesh, Canada, Ghana, Mexico, Sweden and the United States, along with the United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP), who came together to initiate efforts to treat short-lived climate pollutants as an urgent and collective challenge. They formed the Climate & Clean Air Coalition to support fast action and deliver benefits on several fronts at once: climate, public health, energy efficiency, and food security.\n',2125,'2019-05-22 07:59:40',NULL,NULL,0),(1130,1049,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,'PartnerSummary','partners','Having reviewed the documents for the engagement of this partner my comments are as follows:\n1.	This partner has no certificate of incorporation and no article of association uploaded on the partnership portal. I am therefore curious as to why the response on the question: \" are there any risks associated with the registration of this partner\" is \"No\" when there is no document to show that the partner is registered. \n\n2.	The name of the partner in the auditors document is ‘Targa” but the partner is referred to as “Targa Aide” in the partnership portal. It is not clear what the legal name of the partner is. Without the certificate of incorporation or Articles of Association, one cannot know the legal name of the partner. These documents should be obtained from the partner and uploaded on the partnership portal.\n\n3.	The partner has no website and there is no information available for this partner online either to indicate the partners mandate and activities carried out by the partner. In the table under the due diligence the FMO indicates that they have reviewed the website of the partner and found it to be operational and up to date. However, the link for the website for the partner was not provided in the partnership portal. If there is a link, this should be put in the portal so that it can be accessed. \n\n4.	It is not clear from the due diligence what the nature of the engagement with UN Environment is and how is this going to contribute to achieving UN Environment\'s mandate? \n\n5.	In the additional table under the due diligence, the entries indicate that on 3 May 2019, Fatma Twahir, the FMO reviewed the financial statements of the company. However, in the report from the external auditors for the years 1 January to 31 December 2016 (which is in French), the auditors have identified so many inconsistent in the accounts of the partner. \n\n6.	The due diligence indicates that the UN has partnered with Targa Aide 