ution of the CTF budget issues. ',55,'2019-09-26 19:59:02',NULL,NULL,0),(1730,1883,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,'AssesmentQuestions','partners','Based on the additional information provided (attached to the portal) the entity is cleared to proceed',2333,'2019-09-29 20:19:54',NULL,NULL,0),(1731,1883,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,'Comments','partners','Thank you for your review. We understand that you are concerned there is risk SymbioSeas will not be able to fully deliver on a contract with the UN for which only a portion of project costs are covered up-front. We wish to share with you that we are certain we can deliver on contracts with the UN, or any other grantor/funder, for which only a portion of project costs are covered up-front. Our teams are comprised of experts that work at Universities or other non-profits or consultancies. All team members receive base salaries from other employers. All projects led by SymbioSeas are set up with co-financing. For example, for the upcoming SSFA planned with the UN Environment Coral Reef Unit, team members include research scientists from the University of Miami (Ruben van Hooidonk) and from Bangor University (Gareth Williams), both of which are research scientists (Assistant Professor level). Further, for the upcoming SSFA, co-financing is being provided by NOAA. Over the last ~10 years, teams led by Jeff Maynard of SymbioSeas have delivered on ~100 grants and contracts for which only a portion of project costs were covered up-front - all of these projects led to the successful delivery and publication of technical reports or journal articles (see www.symbioseas.org for many examples). Our teams have never failed to deliver on any contract, grant or funding agreement, and always deliver high-impact reports and publications. \n\nSymbioSeas is a small organization that has a part-time accountant that assists with generating financial reports. SymbioSeas is committed to adhering to any and all standards (or \'checks and balances) the UN would like to place in SSFAs or other funding agreements to ensure transparency in accounting. We have written brief responses to the concerns you raised. \n\n•	The explanation provided about the $60K discrepancies indicates carelessness about producing factual financial reports. It is also obvious that the entity does not follow the accrual accounting principles, as they do not reflect (in their 2018 balance sheets), the receivables and future income of the $60K for 2019 from WWF, nor do they include the $20K the receivables and 2019 income from their UN 2018-2019 contract with ROAP.\n\nAs above, SymbioSeas intends to and will adhere to any checks and balances or accounting principles standards the UN recommends or requires in an SSFA or other funding agreement.\n\n•	They also provided some details of their 2018 expenses, which included the $40K they received from their UN 2018-2019 contract with ROAP. I compared these details with the financial report they submitted to ROAP for the $60K contract (ref PO 2700012806), and noted that the partner only reported to ROAP the full $60K as staff costs, while the additional details provided to us showed that some of ROAP income was used to fund their office and utilities costs. This indicates their lack of transparencies to the UN in their financial reporting.\n\nWe always intend to be transparent with our funders in our financial reporting. The concern above relates to internal allocation of funds. For many of our funders, staff costs are reported as salaries but have a percentage as overheads we then use for office space and utilities. Depending on the funder, we might report staff salaries with overheads included or excluded. We will keep this in mind and ensure reporting to the UN separates staff and \'overhead costs\' between salaries and our overhead categories. \n\n•	I also noted that the entity founders do not seem to put their own capital resources into the entity. As shown in their statements and confirmed by the entity, their initial start-up income was $75K cash received from a 2016 grant from NOAA. This indicates lack of sustainability as a going concern, as the entity is entirely dependent on the grants from their partners.\n\nOur organization is small, but is perennially funded by the NOAA Coral Reef Conservation Program. We did not initially put capital resources into the entity but did not need to, as we were in a small office at the time supported through Cornell University, where Jeff Maynard held a position. Projects led by SymbioSeas as the applicant organization are led by teams of experts, all of whom work part-time on the projects and have ongoing support from universities or other conservation organizations. Sustainability of the entity is not a concern due to the small size of the organization and that Director Jeff Maynard and the part-time research assistants and accountant all have other ongoing funding for salaries (which match or serve as co-financing for many funded projects). \n \n•	While the entity reported full expenses of 2018 income ($191,477), it seemed that they have not spent their 2016-2017 income from NOAA, the Nature Conservancy and WWF. I am not sure why they prioritized their 2018 contracts over their older ones, and this raises concerns about their accountability to their partners who must have been waiting for the results of their 2016-2017 contracts.\n\nFunds are expended for projects as needed. Some of our longer-term projects funded in 2016 and 2017 were delivered on in 2019 rather than 2018, with delays due to waiting for climate model data to become available. There are no partners of SymbioSeas projects waiting on results from 2016-2017 contracts; these have been delivered on in 2019 or are ongoing and will be delivered on in 2019 and 2020. \n\n•	In March 2019, the partner reported to UNEP ROAP full expenses of $60K even though they only received $40K from ROAP.  Based on the information provided by the entity, it could be concluded that they pre-financed the $20K for UNEP ROAP contract implementation in 2019 from unspent cash received from their other partners prior to 2018. This also raises more concerns about their accountability to their partners.\n\nThis is incorrect - as explained in the intro paragraph, all contracts and grant agreements led by SymbioSeas required completing projects for which only a portion of the funds were covered up-front. Our own capital is then used to finance the rest of the project to completion and then funders reimburse with their final payment. It is our own capital rather than cash received from other partners that is used to close projects and then we are reimbursed with the final project payment. \n',2656,'2019-09-30 09:05:50',NULL,NULL,0),(1732,1607,2078,0,NULL,2,'AgreementSummary','agreements','I\'ve revised as per advised email.',2116,'2019-09-30 10:42:23',NULL,NULL,0),(1733,1607,2078,0,NULL,2,'AgreementSummary','agreements','I\'ve revised as per advised email.',2116,'2019-09-30 10:42:30',NULL,NULL,0),(1734,1822,1865,NULL,NULL,2,'AgreementSummary','agreements','Annex I, Implementation Plan: dates needs to be adjusted to realistic dates under Activity 1- Strengthening the RAC Association (1 September 2019) and Activity 3 – Coordinating, organizing and implementing training of Customs and law enforcement agents and refrigeration technicians (1 October 2019). Please modify and resubmit. (Recommender)',327,'2019-09-30 12:45:46',NULL,NULL,0),(1735,1816,1866,NULL,NULL,2,'AgreementSummary','agreements','Comment still not addressed. Header says Togo not Comoros (perhaps the wrong file was uploaded). Please revised and resubmit. (Recommender)',327,'2019-09-30 12:49:47',NULL,NULL,0),(1736,1955,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,'AssesmentQuestions','partners','can be approved.',567,'2019-09-30 14:29:14',NULL,NULL,0),(1737,1787,2142,NULL,NULL,2,'AgreementSummary','agreements','update annex, to be in sync with paragraph 3 of the agreement',1958,'2019-09-30 14:46:33',NULL,NULL,0),(1738,1787,2142,