mentSummary','agreements','SSFA with University of Geneva for Provision of content and support for development of IEAGs Monitor using Swiss Funds.',463,'2020-01-16 09:49:15',NULL,NULL,0),(2210,1900,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,'Comments','partners','Dear Juliana, please see the following comments from Isabel for your feedback - In 2015, the UNDP published Mapping Mining to the Sustainable Development Goals: An Atlas as a blueprint for clarifying how mining in general contributes to the SDGs. On the one hand, the report acknowledges that “Tens of millions of people worldwide depend on artisanal and small-scale mining (ASM) for their livelihoods and incomes, far more than depend on large-scale mining (LSM).”41 Yet, on the other hand, the report opts to “focus on large-scale mining” and only discusses ASM “when it directly relates to LSM.” This is a crucial oversight because it paints an inaccurate picture of the role ASM can play developmentally in the world’s resource-rich but poor countries and, in the process, how its growth can help address the SDGs. However, the Atlas is correct in stating that “The scale of ASM warrants a separate guide and review to map the opportunities on how ASM can contribute to the SDGs.” Small-scale mining is extremely detrimental of the environment and of the social conditions of people directly and indirectly involved in the business. The window for UNEP to influence environmental and social improvements in this sector are very challenging, complex and costly. I believe, the partnership with Anexpo in Colombia might give UNEP the opportunity to introduce changes which are beneficial to the environment and concerned people (especially women). In principle, I do support the partnership with Anexpo subject to a risk management plan with particular attention to the branding aspect of the partnership and a close follow-up of the development and outcome of the concrete partnership However, I suggest a call with the UNEP Office in Colombia to learn more about the basis, objectives and scope of the partnership. ',28,'2020-01-16 15:19:50',NULL,NULL,0),(2211,445,2561,NULL,NULL,2,'AgreementSummary','agreements','Abbreviation of TCIS to be explained in the SSFA (available in the AnnexI though).  Reporting deadline should be earlier than the final payment dates.  So if the reporting is due on 30 June, the payment should be within one month from the date of receipt.  SSFA expiry should be minimum 30 October 2020.',577,'2020-01-16 19:12:09',NULL,NULL,0),(2212,2157,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,'AssesmentQuestions','partners','Pls obtain financial report 2016 and 2017 from the partner.  ',577,'2020-01-16 19:18:49',NULL,NULL,0),(2213,2082,2512,NULL,NULL,2,'AgreementSummary','agreements','I have reviewed the legal instrument and below are my comments. Kindly address them and resubmit. \n1.	Under Clause 3-Please provide the results of this intervention. You have only provided the outputs; \n2.	Under Clause 4- Please leave the start date blank. This will enable the system pick up the default phrase ‘date of the latest signature to this agreement’;\n3.	Under Clause 5- Kindly ensure the font is similar for the banking details-Wire Instructions and Signatories;\n4.	Under Clause 7: ‘Reporting’ I note you have 5th June 2020 and 23 January 2021 as the dates for submission of Interim Progress/Financial and Final narrative and financial reports. If this is the case, please synchronize and add the dates to the schedule of payments’\n5.	Under Annexes section, please ensure consistency in labeling the Annexes. See below:\n- Annex 1- Budget and Implementation Plan\n- Annex 2 -Interim Progress Report\n- Annex 3-Final Progress Report\n- Annex 4-Interim and Final Expenditure Report\n6.	In Annex 1: Budget and Implementation Plan- Activity 1, please review the delivery date for the annotated outline of the background report. I believe the date of 5 February 2020 is tight considering the review process of the SSFA and signing process.\nThank you \n (Quality A