02-27 16:45:23',NULL,NULL,0),(2365,967,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,'DueDiligence','partners','Appropriate and correct registration document uploaded. Latest audit report shared which signify no financial risk envisaged. IP cleared for extension.',2507,'2020-02-27 22:25:07',NULL,NULL,0),(2366,1754,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,'Documents','partners','Email received from Luisa Rodriguez Lucas, Legal Officer with MAP on 27 February 2020:\nThis is to kindly request a change in the status of the International Union for Conservation of Nature and Natural Resources (IUCN) -Centre for Mediterranean Cooperation in the Partners Portal from “NGO” to “Inter-governmental Organization” on the basis of the considerations presented below. \n\n(1)	As noted in the audit report of the IUCN Centre for the Mediterranean Cooperation (Informe the Auditoria del Centro the Cooperación del Mediterráneo de la Unión Internacional para la Conservación de la Naturaleza) (see attachment-page 7),  IUCN  is a membership organisation constituted by statutes adopted in 1948 as amended. The membership is comprised of states, governmental agencies, international governmental organizations and national non-governmental organizations. IUCN is registered in Gland, Switzerland as an international association of governmental and non-governmental members under article 60 of the Swiss Civil Code. IUCN Centre for Mediterranean Cooperation is a delegation in Spain of IUCN, and as such is registered before the Spanish Ministry of Interior, as the  certificate of registry (Certificación Registral) (see attachment) accredits together with the tax identification card  (Tarjeta de Indentificación Fiscal)  (see attachment); \n\n(2)	As a delegation in Spain of IUCN, the IUCN-Centre for Mediterranean Cooperation  follows the nature of  IUCN, i.e. an organization the memberships is comprised of states, governmental agencies and governmental and non-governmental organizations. The list of  Mediterranean Members  of IUCN-Centre for Mediterranean Cooperation (https://www.iucn.org/regions/mediterranean/about/mediterranean-members ) reflects this aspect, with most of the Ministries of either Environment or Foreign Affairs of the Contracting Parties to the Barcelona Convention being members of the IUCN-  Centre for Mediterranean Cooperation. This government-membership feature takes particular relevance in Spain. The  Spanish Ministry of Environment as well as several regional governments form part of the  IUCN- Centre for Mediterranean Cooperation. This adds to the fact that the IUCN-Centre for Mediterranean Cooperation was established within the framework of a MOU among the IUCN, the Spanish Ministry of Environment, the Spanish Agency for International Cooperation of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, and the Regional Government of Andalusia. This is pointed out in page 7 of  the audit report of the IUCN Centre for the Mediterranean Cooperation (Informe the Auditoria del Centro the Cooperación del Mediterráneo de la Unión Internacional para la Conservación de la Naturaleza). \n\nAll the documents attached are already in the Partnership Portal. This email provides for your consideration additional information to justify the rectification of the status of  IUCN -Centre for Mediterranean Cooperation in the Partners Portal from “NGO” to “Inter-governmental Organization”. \n',17,'2020-02-28 11:27:58',NULL,NULL,0),(2367,274,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,'Documents','partners','Email from Maria Luisa Rodriguez Lucas, Legal Officer with MAP, on 27 February 2020:\n\nFollowing our conversation, and action subsequently taken,  for record-keeping purposes, please find below line of events and associated attached documents supporting  the status of  SPA/RAC under the Partners Portal  as “government/governmental” rather than “NGO”.  \n\n(1)	The intergovernmental meeting on Mediterranean Specially Protected Areas (Athens, 1980) (UNEP/IG. 20/5) recommended  to the Coastal States of the Mediterranean: (a) to establish (…) a regional activity center for the Mediterranean protected areas within the framework of activities of the secretariat in charge of coordinating the Mediterranean Action Plan (MAP), and (b) to accept the generous offer of the government of the Tunisian Republic to act as host to the centre in Tunis (Source: UNEP/IG. 56/INF. 8-See attachment); \n(2)	The second meeting of the Contracting Parties (Cannes, 1981) (UNEP/IG. 23/11)  approved the establishment of the regional centre and accepted the offer of Tunisia to host it. The meeting took the view that the Centre would be established and would operate as a national institution with a regional role to play, like the Regional Activity Centres already in operation as part of MAP. (Source: UNEP/IG. 56/INF. 8-See attachment);\n(3)	As the 1991 Agreement between the Government of Tunisia and UNEP as amended  states in its preamble (see attachment), RAC/SPA was established in 1985 as a national center with a regional role, through which the Government of Tunisia contributed to the Mediterranean Action Plan (MAP).  The Agreement further emphasizes this point in its operative paragraph 1, by providing that RAC/SPA will be managed and operated under the control of the Ministry of Environment  as a Tunisian national institution with a regional role as recognized and defined by the Contracting Parties to the Barcelona Convention; \n(4)	Consequently with the nature so defined, COP Decision IG. 19/5, adopted by the 16th Meeting of the Contracting Parties to the Barcelona Convention (Marrakech, 3-5 November 2009) (see attachment), defines  the regional role of RAC/SPA in assisting countries to implement the 1982 Protocol concerning Specially Protected Areas in the Mediterranean, amended by the  1995 Protocol concerning Specially Protected Areas and Biological Diversity in the Mediterranean (the “SPA/Biodiversity Protocol”). More specifically, the role of  RAC/SPA is to provide assistance to the Contracting Parties in meeting their obligations under Articles 4 and 10 of the Barcelona Convention, 1995, and under SPA/BD Protocol; as well as in implementing the Strategic Action Programme for the Conservation of Biological Biodiversity in the Mediterranean Region (SAP BIO), adopted by the Contracting Parties in 2003, and the Mediterranean Strategy for Sustainable Development. \n(5)	Under the previous PCA between UNEP and RAC/SPA (See attachment), RAC/SPA was defined as a non-profit oriented and non-partisan organization. The former PCA was signed by the Director of the RAC/SPA, which is a a clear sign of RAC/SPA having its own legal personality.',17,'2020-02-28 11:34:14',NULL,NULL,0),(2368,273,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,'Documents','partners','Email from Maria Luisa Rodriguez Lucas, Legal Officer with MAP, dated 27 February 2020:\n\nThis email refers to the key documents supporting the change in status in the Partners Portal as regards the Priority Actions Programme /Regional Activity Centre (PAP/RAC) from “NGOs” to “Government/Governmental”. Documents attached will be uploaded in the Portal from our side by today.   \n\n(1)	1996 Agreement between the Republic of Croatia and UNEP concerning PAP/RAC (see attachment). The Agreement lists in its preamble the steps which led to the establishment of PAP/RAC by the Government of the former Federal Republic of Yugoslavia (SFRY) as a national centre with a regional role. The point of departure is the decision of the Contracting Parties to the Barcelona Convention at their intergovernmental meeting of on the Blue Plan (Split 1977) to accept the offer by the former SFRY to host a regional center in Split relevant to a Priority Actions Programme.  On that basis,  the Government of SFRY adopted a decree announcing the establishment of  PAP/RAC.  The operative part of the Agreement reflects well the nature of the centre as defined in the preamble, by pointed out that the centre, as a Croatian institute,  shall act pursuant the decision of the Contracting Parties to the Barcelona Convention as a RAC entrusted with the implementation of the  Priority Actions Programme, as part of the MAP. \n\n(2)	COP Decision IG. 19/5, adopted by the 16th Meeting of the Contracting Parties to the Barcelona Convention (Marrakech, 3-5 November 2009) (see attachment). Decision IG. 19/5 details  the regional role of PAP/SPA in  providing assistance to Mediterranean countries in the implementation of the Barcelona Convention, the Integrated Coastal Zone Management Protocol as well as the  Mediterranean Strategy for Sustainable Development. \n\n(3)	PCA between UNEP and PAP/RAC (see attachment). Under the previous PCA between UNEP and PAP/RAC , PAP/RAC was defined as a non-profit oriented and non-partisan organization. The former PCA was signed by the Director of the PAP/RAC, which is a  clear indication of PAP/RAC having its own legal personality. ',17,'2020-02-28 11:38:59',NULL,NULL,0),(2369,1539,2665,NULL,NULL,2,'AgreementSummary','agreements','I have reviewed the legal instrument and below are my comments. Kindly address them and resubmit.\n1.	In the Preamble: 4th paragraph, which reads in part, “Based on the Resolutions 1/6 “ Marine plastic debris and microplastics”,2/11 …”, third sentence, kindly remove the full stop after the word ”Assembly”.\n2.	Under Clause 4: ‘ Starting and ending dates for implementation of the activities:’, Kindly enter a valid end date.\n3.	Under Annexes section, please ensure consistency in labeling the Annexes. See below:- ANNEX A- ensure you save your document as “ Budget and Implementation Plan” which will appear “ANNEX A: Budget and Implementation Plan”- ANNEX B- ensure you save your document as “ ANNEX B : Final Financial Report” which will appear “ANNEX B : Final Financial Report” - Additional Annexes-ensure you save your document as “ ANNEX C: Final Progress Report” which will appear “ANNEX C: Final Progress Report” .\n\nThank you \n (Quality Assurance)',2112,'2020-02-29 12:38:26',NULL,NULL,0),(2370,2250,2703,0,NULL,2,'AgreementDocuments'