e medium risks, ',2125,'2020-10-06 12:02:34',NULL,NULL,0),(3128,1335,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,'Comments','partners','MoU looks ok to me and ready for signature',1194,'2020-10-06 12:12:54',NULL,NULL,0),(3129,2529,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,'Agreements','partners','Polite Prompting-QA comments were addressed and resubmitted on 02/10.  Hope the Agreement is now okay. Thank you.',261,'2020-10-06 12:42:08',NULL,NULL,0),(3130,2309,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,'Comments','partners','NOTE REGARDING IMPLEMENTATION/EXECUTION ARRANGEMENTS WITH THE PARTNER:\nRecent audits concerning GEF projects (mainly from the Climate Adaptation and Biodiversity and Land Degradation Units in Ecosystems Division) have indicated considerable delays in payments managed by the Executing Agency (the Vice-President’s Office, represented by the Ministry of Finance and Planning). These delays are affecting project delivery. The Government recently announced that they have now completed the D-Fund registration (new system of consolidating official development assistance with the Ministry of Finance). Despite this positive development, the delays are unlikely to be sorted as there are complementary risks related to current practices in decision making and delegation of authority. At the moment, all decisions concerning payments above Tzh 3 million (US$1,300) go to the Permanent Secretary or OIC, including authorizing payments of consultants. There are also informal complaints by international consulting firms on communications and transacting with VPO. These issues are related to payments that are delayed by several months, withholding taxes that were not reflected in contracts, and currency issues. These are still in the process of being resolved though and no conclusions on any wrongdoing have been made. There have also been delays and challenges for VPO to establish effective MOUs with other Government agencies charged with implementation activities on the ground, resulting in implementation progressing very slowly and mainly at the central level. It will be therefore critical to closely monitoring these risks to ensure that this GEF child project can be implemented in a timely fashion under these regulations. This is because this project is part of a global GEF program, with another 10 country child projects running in parallel. An early MTR will be considered to assess whether adequate progress is being made under the PCA arrangements.',1103,'2020-10-06 18:30:05',NULL,NULL,0),(3131,2205,3102,0,NULL,2,'PreAssessment','agreements','Dear Charuwan,\nThanks for your clarifications below, all fine with me.\nI will return to you.\nBest.\nIsabel\n\nFrom: Charuwan Tintukasiri  \nSent: Wednesday, October 07, 2020 6:35 AM\nTo: Isabel Martinez \nCc: Shaofeng Hu ; Pipat Poopeerasupong ; Kherlenzaya Ariunbold \nSubject: RE: Legal Review of 2020-UN2UN_AFG/PHA/85/TAS/27 HCFC Phase-out Management Plan (stage I, fourth tranche) in Afghanistan (A3102)\n\nDear Ms. Isabel,\nThank you so much for your kind review.  I provided the response down below in red.  Please help review if it is OK, then I can add in the Agreement when you return it to me.\nWith best regards,\nCharuwan\n\nFrom: Isabel Martinez  \nSent: Tuesday, October 6, 2020 2:32 AM\nTo: Charuwan Tintukasiri \nSubject: RE: Legal Review of 2020-UN2UN_AFG/PHA/85/TAS/27 HCFC Phase-out Management Plan (stage I, fourth tranche) in Afghanistan (A3102)\n\nDear Charuwan,\n\nAs to the Annex, the original UN to UN agreement does not include the provision you have mentioned below (see attached the UN to UN agreement template available on WeCollaborate/legal, here. Therefore, it is correct to delete the reference to such Annex. Normally the reference to annexes or listing of annexes is made in section A. SUMMARY OF ACTIVITIES, Annexes.\n\nPlease find below some other comments:\n\n1.	A -Summary of activities, start/end date: It is advisable that the end date of activities is prior to the date of submission of the final financial report and overall conclusion of t