his section.\n3.	Under Article 9 Paragraph (1), we observed that you have deleted the section on non-authorization of use of UNEP/UN name and emblem for commercial purposes. We note that the partner is not-for-profit however we cannot authorize the use of the organisation name and logo for commercial purposes, and we need to have it stated in the agreement thus revise Paragraph (1) to read as below:\n‘Neither Party shall use the name, emblem or trademarks of the other Party, its subsidiaries and/or affiliates, or any abbreviation thereof, in connection with its business or for public dissemination without the prior expressly written approval of the other Party in each case. In no event shall authorization of the UN or UNEP name or emblem be granted for commercial purposes.’\n4.	Under Article 12 on responsibility, we note that Paragraph (2) of the template has been deleted. Please consider that this is a boilerplate provision for us, and we CANNOT accept ANY changes to this provision. Therefore, include the following paragraph: \nASU shall indemnify, hold and save harmless and defend at its own expense, the United Nations and UNEP, their officials, personnel and representatives, from and against all suits, claims, demands and liability of any nature or kind which may arise in relation to this MOU due to any actions or omissions attributable to ASU.\n5.	Under Article 13 on Dispute Settlement, we note that our standard Dispute Settlement has been deleted. While the proposed provision has a reference on settle disputes amicably, we cannot accept the proposed provisions as it refers to non-binding arbitration in accordance with applicable laws and court rules. Please consider that due to UNEP’s legal status, we CANNOT be subject to any national legislation as acceptance of such a provision would imply UNEP’s waiver to the UN Privileges and Immunities which we are not authorized to do. Thus, we would suggest retaining the original text on alternate dispute settlements through arbitration in accordance with UNCITRAL Arbitration. In addition, Article VIII, Section 29 of the Convention on the Privileges and Immunities of the United Nations provides that, “the United Nations shall make provisions for appropriate modes of settlement of (a) disputes arising out of contracts or other disputes of a private law character to which the United Nations is a party; (b) disputes involving any official of the United Nations who by reason of his official position enjoys immunity, if immunity has not been waived by the Secretary-General.” This provision is the basis for the arbitration and dispute resolution clauses set forth in all United Nations (and UNEP) contracts. Although the United Nations does not agree to waive its privileges and immunities in its contracts, by agreeing to arbitrate disputes of a private law character as a full and final resolution thereof, such as disputes arising out of contracts, the United Nations is providing for an “appropriate mode of settlement” of such dispute. Thus, such a dispute resolution mechanism fulfills the Organization’s requirements under Section 29 of the Convention to provide an appropriate mode of settlement of disputes arising out of contracts to which the United Nations (in this case UNEP) is a party.\n6.	Please review the formatting of the MOU since slight editing is required in few parts.\n \n\n',3165,'2021-06-07 17:25:26',NULL,NULL,0),(4010,2629,4135,NULL,NULL,2,'AgreementSummary','agreements','Kindly review the draft SSFA and the budget/implementation plan; several of the deliverable dates are already post-facto.\n\nSecondly, the entire budget is almost 99% personnel in nature which contravenes the partnership policy. If you wish to proceed as is, an exceptional approval has to be obtained from the Corporate services division vide a memo through the RD.',55,'2021-06-07 17:35:47',NULL,NULL,0),(4011,2840,4175,0,NULL,2,'AgreementSummary','agreements','Dear Nada, for your clearance. with best regards.