','partners','Dear @Isabel Martinez\n\nThank you for your comments.\nI would like to respond those 3 items as follows:\nResponse for 1: Rakuten, Inc. also has been taking various activities to tackle global challenges and achieve a sustainable future which are similar to the MTS 2022-2025 and the PoW 2022-2023. For example, they join the international initiative, “Renewable Electricity 100% (RE100”), and they aim at completing to switch to 100% renewable electricity at its offices, data centers and fulfillment centers by 2025. Regarding biodiversity, Rakuten follows all local and relevant international laws on animals and wildlife, including international conventions such as the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species of Wild Fauna and Flora (CITES) and comprehensive regulations such as Japan’s Act for the Conservation of Endangered Species of Wild Fauna and Flora. Regarding resource management, they we aim to use the most appropriate package size according to product dimensions in order to minimize the use of materials. Also they procure and use cardboard boxes made from 90 to 95% recycled paper as specified by Japanese standards. In addition, inflatable packing materials (air pillows) are used as cushioning solutions to protect products for some deliveries, an environmentally-friendly alternative to other materials.\nIETC recognises that their activities will support UNEP’s activities on the three planetary crises at national, regional and global levels because of not only their operation whose core is sustainability but also their global network among 30 countries and their customers (about 1.4 billion).\n\nResponse for 2: As od October 2021, IETC plans to conduct various outreach activities to disseminate of environmentally sound management of waste for recycling and sustainability in daily lives in collaboration with Rakuten Inc. For example, their e-commerce is the largest e-commerce industry, namely they provide infrastructure of daily shopping in Japan. By using their largest e-commerce, it is possible to share information why we need to take actions on sustainability to combat the three planetary crises. Also IETC aims at creating a new opportunity not only for UNEP to change people’s behaviour but also for Rakuten and other companies who do not work together but work together with UNEP to change their customers’ behaviour on sustainability. For this plan, IETC and them have been continuing discussion on next steps, including MOU.\n\nResponse for 3: as indicated our response to Question 15, they sell tobacco alcohol pursuant to laws and regulations in each jurisdiction. In their Rakuten Shopping Webs, every customer needs to register to use all the services in Rakuten Shopping Webs. If costumers are minors less than 18 years old in Japan, they need to get first approval from their parents and submit its certificate to get approval from Rakuten Inc. before accessing any services. We hope this clarifies this question for the Private Sector Unit. Dear @Mohammed Mabrouk: could you give us your opinions?\n\nBest regards,\n\nShunichi Honda',636,'2021-10-08 02:52:31',NULL,NULL,0),(4594,3005,4733,NULL,NULL,2,'AgreementSummary','agreements','Dear Rowan, please align dates with the word doc thanks',29,'2021-10-08 13:21:05',NULL,NULL,0),(4595,2536,4737,NULL,NULL,2,'AgreementSummary','agreements','Yuki: Please amend clause 14 to reflect 3 months.',2507,'2021-10-08 14:14:13',NULL,NULL,0),(4596,1154,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,'PartnerSummary','partners','I refer to the notification  received today from the Portal to  finalize the assessment for agreement 1154 as a Partnership Committee member. Since the partner\'s due diligence will expire in a month and the most recent financial statement is for the period 2015-2017 I suggest to initiate a new due diligence process or at least submit updated information about the partner. Namely: most recent financial statement; most recent annual substantive report and a short summary (1 page or so) of results of the current engagement.',2079,'2021-10-08 17:48:48',NULL,NULL,0),(4597,207,4486,0,NULL,2,'AgreementSummary','agreements','Dear Thomas, over to you for your kind review. Changes to the boilerplate clause (IPR) have been done following our earlier discussions.',845,'2021-10-08 18:56:21',NULL,NULL,0),(4598,207,4486,0,NULL,2,'AgreementSummary','agreements','Dear Nina, there are 3 slight changes that need to be made to the agreement. \n1) The preamble says: Based on the UN Environment Assembly (UNEA) resolution 3/10 on \'Addressing water pollution to protect and restore water-related ecosystems\' (UNEP/EA.3/Res.10) between UNEP and Helmholtz-Centre for Environmental Research (UFZ)... The UNEA resolution was not between UNEP and UFZ, this mention needs to be deleted; \n2) At paragraph 7, I would suggest listing the reports by chronological order. \n3) Finally, at paragraph 9.a.i), the article grants the partner a licence for \"at least 5 years\". This is unclear because it gives an open-ended use to the partner, without indicating how or when could UNEP terminate the licence, should it wish to do so. I would suggest saying either \"for 5 years\", or \"for XX years\" with a higher number, or finally propose a perpetual licence if this is in UNEP\'s interest. ',3039,'2021-10-11 12:06:58',NULL,NULL,0),(4599,1384,4657,0,NULL,2,'AgreementSummary','agreements','Dear Nada, for your kind review and clearance from FMO side.',845,'2021-10-12 08:57:43',NULL,NULL,0),(4600,1154,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,'PartnerSummary','partners','On 12/10/2021, Erika Mattsson confirmed by email to me: \"The audited financial statement from 2019 demonstrates that the partner has actually grown and become financially stronger due to the number of project grants that they are implementing for example for UNIDO/GEF, German Society for International Cooperation, EU, UNDP etc. From the financial perspective it’s fine.\"',2079,'2021-10-12 16:30:49',NULL,NULL,0),(4601,1550,4560,NULL,NULL,2,'A