 information in English language media and a lack of reporting in RepRisk and Sustainalytics has been a challenge with some Chinese entities. Because of this, we reached out to the China office for additional research help. Ruihe and Qi kindly supported this effort and did a review using search tools available, including Google, Baidu and Tianyancha. They provided the following information:\nFor a publicly listed business, if it was punished by governmental authorities, it must release the punishment information. In the case of China Tianying, it went publicly listed in China\'s Shenzhen Stock Exchange through reverse takeover in 2014. The search result indicates no negative news for Tianying.\nA positive news for Tianying, released by China Environment News (a national newspaper running on working days, based in Beijing), July 22, 2021, is that Tianying is among the top 3 environment protection enterprises in China, which is available at  https://www.cenews.com.cn/newpos/202107/t20210722_978727.html\nFocal point of Tianying for us confirmed from its HQ that no record of warnings or punishments by Chinese government authorities.  \nI incorporated these points into our assessment, but please let me know if there are additional questions I can address. \nKind regards,\nSarah\nFrom: Daniel Cooney  \nSent: Thursday, October 14, 2021 10:17 AM\nTo: Sarah Bons ; Andrina Beaumond (Affiliate) \nCc: Atif Ikram Butt ; Ruihe Tu ; Qi Qin ; Atif Ikram Butt ; Alejandra Perez ; Sonja Leighton-Kone ; Alexander Juras ; Thomas Didier Paul Deleuil ; Isabel Martinez \nSubject: Re: Champion of the Earth Award - question on selection process\nDear Sarah,\nI am better placed to answer this. \nHere is my response (as Director of the Communication Division, and not as a member of the Partnership Committee):\n“If the Partnership Committee approves this partnership, the next step would be for the Communication Division, together with the Asia-Pacific office (the lead on this proposed partnership), to develop a detailed sponsorship plan with the company for Champions of the Earth. It would detail the brand visibility that the company would get from the sponsorship, and it would make clear that the company would have zero influence in the selection of the Champion laureates. The company and the Chinese government would not be consulted in the entire selection process. Once the proposed sponsorship plan is finalized with the company, the plan would be presented to the ED for approval before any sponsorship agreement is signed.”\nSeparate to this query, and now wearing my other hat as a member of the Partnership Committee, why is no RepRisk report nor a Sustainalytics report available for this company? The Comms Division has done a substantive desk review of what we can find online about the company, but it is very limited. \nI copy Dechen into this given the role of the Asia-Pacific office, as well as Sonja, Alexander, Isabel and Thomas as other members of the Partnership Committee.\nDan\nFrom: Sarah Bons \nDate: Thursday, 14 October 2021 at 09:31\nTo: Andrina Beaumond (Affiliate) \nCc: Daniel Cooney , Atif Ikram Butt , Ruihe Tu , Qi Qin \nSubject: Champion of the Earth Award - question on selection process\nDear Andrina,\nI hope this email finds you well. I am from the Private Sector Unit and we are assessing a potential private sector partner that has expressed interest in sponsoring the Champion of the Earth award as part of a potential partnership (I have been working with Qi Qin and Ruihe Tu on this partner). A member of our Partnership Committee asked the following question:\nKindly provide information how it will be ensured that the sponsor will not influence the Champion of the Earth selection process, e.g. if there is a candidate that would not get endorsement from the Chinese Government. Will UNEP be able to operate freely and without undue influence if we accepted this support?\n\nIt was suggested I reach out to you to get more information on the selection process. Could you kindly address the below questions:\nFrom the perspective of procedures/process of selection, is there any possibility for the sponsor to influence formally or informally?  Is there any step to consult the sponsor?  Is there any step to consult the government of the concerned member state? Is there any step to consult the government of the awardee’s nationality? To our best knowledge and based on experiences in the last a few years, the selection process is handled by only a few staff and is kept it in a secret till open announcement. \nMany thanks in advance!\nKind regards,\nSarah',3197,'2021-10-20 14:24:22',NULL,NULL,0),(4640,2188,4518,NULL,NULL,2,'AgreementSummary','agreements','Given the ongoing discussions in relation to the regional consultations and the inclusion of 6 regional consultations in this agreement, I am doubtful we would be able to undertake all of them before April 2022 (concluding date of this agreement). I would like to suggest a possible extension of this agreement until June 2022 to offer more flexibility to finalize the consultations.  (Quality Assurance)',76,'2021-10-20 15:50:16',NULL,NULL,0),(4641,2560,4248,NULL,NULL,2,'AgreementSummary','agreements','Pls action per email',55,'2021-10-20 17:15:35',NULL,NULL,0),(4642,2686,4775,0,NULL,2,'AgreementSummary','agreements','Dear Yanelit. Thank you for the draft.  Please find comment to improve the SSFA: \n- 2. a. iv.  Ozone depleting substances (ODS) regulations - Place place capital letters for Ozone Depleting Substances. \n- I am unsure where the dates in the due dates come from, meaning the actual day.  For example, for 2i, the PI has a date of 16 December 2022.  No dates were provided in the draft SSFA endorsed and PIs do not usually actually days except when they are specific. Those days are quite random. Please remove all the references to days in the PI targets.  For example, the first target date in the SSFA should be December 2022. The second one should be Ju